	"__INITIAL_DATA__": {"comments":{"id":26981,"count":133,"talk_id":2361},"threadId":26981,"current_talk":"2361","description":"You're not at your best when you're stressed. In fact, your brain has evolved over millennia to release cortisol in stressful situations, inhibiting rational, logical thinking but potentially helping you survive, say, being attacked by a lion. Neuroscientist Daniel Levitin thinks there's a way to avoid making critical mistakes in stressful situations, when your thinking becomes clouded -- the pre-mortem. \"We all are going to fail now and then,\" he says. \"The idea is to think ahead to what those failures might be.\"","event":"TEDGlobal>London","language":"en","name":"Daniel Levitin: How to stay calm when you know you'll be stressed","slug":"daniel_levitin_how_to_stay_calm_when_you_know_you_ll_be_stressed","speakers":[{"id":"2660","slug":"daniel_levitin","is_published":true,"firstname":"Daniel","lastname":"Levitin","middleinitial":"","title":"","description":"Neuroscientist","photo_url":"https://pe.tedcdn.com/images/ted/05e286731c43769d6d0b07337b39c6e488f58d35_254x191.jpg","whatotherssay":"","whotheyare":"Daniel Levitin incorporates findings from neuroscience into everyday life.","whylisten":"<p>Dr. Daniel Levitin is a neuroscientist at McGill University in Montreal, dean at Minerva Schools in San Francisco and a musician. His research focuses on pattern processing in the brain.</p><p>His three books&nbsp;<a href=\"http://geni.us/brainonmusic\" target=\"_blank\"><em>This Is Your Brain on Music</em></a>,&nbsp;<a href=\"http://geni.us/worldinsixsongs\" target=\"_blank\"><em>The World in Six Songs</em></a>, and the recent&nbsp;<a href=\"http://geni.us/organizedmind\" target=\"_blank\"><em>The Organized Mind</em></a>&nbsp;are all bestsellers. A polymath at heart, he has performed with top musicians and holds a few gold and platinum records.</p><p>Levitin earned his B.A. in Cognitive Psychology and Cognitive Science at Stanford University, and went on to earn his Ph.D. in Psychology from the University of Oregon, researching complex auditory patterns and pattern processing in expert and non-expert populations. He completed post-doctoral training at Stanford University Medical School (in Neuroimaging) and at UC Berkeley (in Cognitive Psychology). He has consulted on audio sound source separation for the U.S. Navy, and on audio quality for several rock bands and record labels (including the Grateful Dead and Steely Dan), and served as one of the &ldquo;Golden Ears&rdquo; expert listeners in the original Dolby AC3 compression tests. He worked for two years at the Silicon Valley think tank Interval Research Corporation.</p><p>He taught at Stanford University in the Department of Computer Science, the Program in Human-Computer Interaction, and the Departments of Psychology, Anthropology, Computer Music, and History of Science.&nbsp;</p>"}],"url":"https://www.ted.com/talks/daniel_levitin_how_to_stay_calm_when_you_know_you_ll_be_stressed","viewed_count":11667461,"talks":[{"recommendations":{"status":"approved","headline":"Daniel Levitin recommends","blurb":"Resources and inspirations behind Daniel Levitin's TED Talk.","start_at":null,"end_at":null,"published":true,"eyebrow":null,"type":"recommendation","rec_lists":[{"title":"Reading list","description":"","rec_items":[{"label":"READ_Book","headline":"Your Medical Mind: How to Decide What Is Right for You","blurb":"Groopman and Hartzband demystify the process of medical decision making -- and make it easier to have conversations with medical professionals about the decisions that matter most.","note":"Jerome Groopman and Pamela Hartzband\r\nPenguin Books, 2012","link_url":"http://www.amazon.com/Your-Medical-Mind-Decide-Right/dp/014312224X/ref=as_li_tf_tl?ie=UTF8&camp=1789&creative=9325&creativeASIN=0520271440&linkCode=as2&tag=teco06-20","position":null,"is_pdf":false,"eyebrow":null},{"label":"READ_Book","headline":"The Organized Mind: Thinking Straight in the Age 